  "description": "Changing basis to make sense of a dimeric system.",
  "body_html": "<p>Hey guys! I\u2019ve been wanting to post more of my technical work. I will link details, but write about the aims, motivations and content here. My technical <a href=\"https://casualphysicsenjoyer.com/Essays+in+progress/Computational+chemistry/Stylised+Toy+Example+of+the+Diabatisation+Procedure\">post is here</a>. </p><p>My main project is predicting what happens when polarised light shines on a protein. This is called <a href=\"https://chem.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Physical_and_Theoretical_Chemistry_Textbook_Maps/Supplemental_Modules_(Physical_and_Theoretical_Chemistry)/Spectroscopy/Electronic_Spectroscopy/Circular_Dichroism\">circular dichroism spectroscopy</a>. It\u2019s a fast way to get some basic structural information about a a protein, albeit less accurate. </p><p>It\u2019s really hard to do this calculation quantum mechanically for long proteins, so we split them up into chunks called dimers. Each dimer is comprised of two smaller chunks called monomers, joined together at a particular angle. For each type of dimer, our computers are strong enough to compute their properties in reasonable time. </p><p>But our programs to get the properties of a molecule are blunt. When we use a computer to get the energies of a dimer, we get some information, like its energies, and the first order direction of their charge. </p><p>But this isn\u2019t in the format that we need it. This diagonal matrix tells us properties about the dimer as a whole, but not how two, separate monomers interact. For example, consider two monomers joined together by a peptide bond.</p><p>We want to the interaction information, so that when we chain these monomers together for the protein, so we know how each link in the chain affects the next one. </p><div class=\"captioned-image-container\"><figure><a class=\"image-link image2 is-viewable-img\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!tkhF!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png\" data-component-name=\"Image2ToDOM\"><div class=\"image2-inset\"><picture><source type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!tkhF!,w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!tkhF!,w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!tkhF!,w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!tkhF!,w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\"><img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!tkhF!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png\" width=\"790\" height=\"590\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:590,&quot;width&quot;:790,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:22266,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:&quot;https://chillphysicsenjoyer.substack.com/i/172657953?img=https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png&quot;,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false,&quot;align&quot;:null,&quot;offset&quot;:false}\" class=\"sizing-normal\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!tkhF!,w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!tkhF!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!tkhF!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!tkhF!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fc3761e4e-6b78-4ec7-ba73-92ea27fe6a60_790x590.png 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\" fetchpriority=\"high\"></picture><div class=\"image-link-expand\"><div class=\"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset\"><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container restack-image\"><svg role=\"img\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 20 20\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke=\"var(--color-fg-primary)\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><g><title></title><path d=\"M2.53001 7.81595C3.49179 4.73911 6.43281 2.5 9.91173 2.5C13.1684 2.5 15.9537 4.46214 17.0852 7.23684L17.6179 8.67647M17.6179 8.67647L18.5002 4.26471M17.6179 8.67647L13.6473 6.91176M17.4995 12.1841C16.5378 15.2609 13.5967 17.5 10.1178 17.5C6.86118 17.5 4.07589 15.5379 2.94432 12.7632L2.41165 11.3235M2.41165 11.3235L1.5293 15.7353M2.41165 11.3235L6.38224 13.0882\"></path></g></svg></button><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container view-image\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-maximize2 lucide-maximize-2\"><polyline points=\"15 3 21 3 21 9\"></polyline><polyline points=\"9 21 3 21 3 15\"></polyline><line x1=\"21\" x2=\"14\" y1=\"3\" y2=\"10\"></line><line x1=\"3\" x2=\"10\" y1=\"21\" y2=\"14\"></line></svg></button></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p>So, we can use math to \u2018change basis\u2019 to get into into a different form, where we can read off the couplings that we associate with a particular interpretation. I found the literature and exposition of this procedure pretty light. As such, <a href=\"https://casualphysicsenjoyer.com/Essays+in+progress/Computational+chemistry/Stylised+Toy+Example+of+the+Diabatisation+Procedure\">I wrote a small note on such a procedure, where we can compute the properties of two small monomers joined by a bond, here.</a></p>",
